          <h2>Category teasers</h2>
          <hr />

          <div class="content-container">
            <h3>Usage</h3>
            <p>A category teaser is used to spotlight content further within the site. They can be used for categories within the exchange and rewards landing page or elsewhere as standard teasers.</p>
            <h4>Interactions</h4>
            <p>There is a soft hover state on the teaser image and teasers contain a clickable area to form a large button link.</p>
            <h4>Layout modes</h4>
            <p>There are three layout modes: desktop, tablet and mobile. Larger screens have a 3 row layout. Multiple items above 3 will stack in rows underneath. Tablet screens stack items vertically in a fluid stretching format. Smaller screens display the individual teaser items in the same way as the larger screen but in a vertically stacked format.</p>
            <hr />
            <h3>CSS</h3>
            <h4>Media queries</h4>
            <p>We are using three breakpoints to handle the changes between desktop, tablet and mobile. Common styles are loaded for the component and then device specific styles are loaded in for each breakpoint into the appropriate stylesheet.</p>
            <h4>SASS Partials</h4>
            <p>You can find the CSS for this component in the following SASS Partials:</p>
            <p>/common-components/category-teaser.scss</p>
            <p>/large-components/category-teaser.scss</p>
            <p>/tablet-components/category-teaser.scss</p>
            <p>/small-components/category-teaser.scss</p>
            <hr />
            <h3>Component variants</h3>
            <p>Teasers can either user the default Tesco blue as background or be colour coded to match the product category secondary colour palette.</p>
            <hr />
            <h3>Responsive Images</h3>
            <p>We are using the responsive masking technique on tablet to preserve the height of the object but reduce the width of the image in a fluid container. The mobile image needs to be as wide as the largest breakpoint (600px) so in this instance we do not recommend using WURFL to replace the image for mobile devices.</p>
